For those who feel like picking this game up again here is how you crazy dash and crazy drift.

Crazy dash: release the gas and put the car into reverse and then quickly put the car in drive and press the gas.

Crazy Drift: As you are turning do not release the gas. Quickly shift between reverse and back to drive. For a longer drift keep holding the turn

text:
OKAY SO.

Scooby-Doo! and the Witches Ghost was released October 5th, 1999. A true masterpiece of film. It featured some of the best characters in Scooby-Doo canon, The Hex Girls, and Ben Ravencroft, played masterfully by Tim Curry at his absolute BEST. I can still quote his speech at the climax of the story word for word.

‚ÄúBecause it ISN‚ÄôT, Velma. It‚Äôs a speeeeeeeeeeeelbook. You see, Sarah wasn‚Äôt a Wiccan, she was indeed‚Ä¶ a witch!  And since Sarah's blood runs through my veins, I guess that makes ME (inhales) a warlock!‚Äù

Truly this scene is vitally important to the integrity of all cinema. However, I am getting off topic. The fact at hand, is that the Hex Girls originated from Scooby-Doo! and the Witches Ghost. While I appreciate the fact that The Hex Girls had an appearance in Scooby Doo! and the Legend of the Vampire, which came out on March 4th, 2003, to say that the Hex Girls are FROM said movie, and not from Scooby-Doo! and the Witches Ghost is simply a GROSS misunderstanding of Scooby-Doo canon, and brings SHAME to all true Scooby-Doo fans. I request that Gura issue a correction of this SLANDEROUS mistake at once, before others begin to believe that such an inferior movie could ever produce a group of wonderful characters like the Hex Girls.
